bug.short_desc: [regression] Gerrit editor shows error when offline

long_desc.thetext: When I don't have network connectivity the Gerrit editor shows an error popup when opening the editor and an error message in the header "Error opening task". It should fail gracefully and show the review details that were cached.

I'm thinking this is closely related to bug 399434 ??, e.g. not actually a regression since it never seems to have worked..?

This has nothing to do with bug 399434. Steps:
1. Disconnect from network 2. Open review from task list
Having some level of offline support and graceful handling of lack of network connectivity is a key feature of Mylyn and it's no longer working for reviews.

(In reply to comment #4) > Having some level of offline support and graceful handling of lack of network > connectivity is a key feature of Mylyn and it's no longer working for reviews.
I'm not asserting that it's not an important issue, I'm just saying that it looks like there are a number of cases where we're not failing gracefully.
We're in an awkward in between state right now. Since we are no longer relying on loading the model from the local task store, we don't have the big json blob that we were once storing in task data and could recover previously retrieved task data from. And we don't yet have the model persistence implemented (though I do have it working experimentally), which means that we don't have a backing store right now at all. So proper offline support is going to be absent until we get that. In the experimental review, this is already failing more gracefully and the final implementation will handle this case appropriately.
Thanks for calling attention to the issue.

It's fine that the task editor shows less information if that's no longer cached. It's not acceptable though that it shows a modal dialog when working offline. Miles, this should be addressed for Kepler M6, e.g. by showing a short error message in the editor section.
It's *very important* that existing functionality and workflows continue to work even as we make bigger changes to the code. Sometimes that means we have to make a little bit of extra effort to add some error handling that will later be obsolete. We are regularly releasing integration builds of Mylyn on the weekly site and as part of Eclipse release train milestones so it's important that we work out regressions of this sort quickly.

(In reply to comment #6) > It's fine that the task editor shows less information if that's no longer > cached. It's not acceptable though that it shows a modal dialog when working > offline.
You mean, like say what Bugzilla connector does when I try to synchronize? (Looks pretty modal to me...)
Miles, please take another look at the description. I am requesting that it is possible to _open_ the editor when offline without getting a modal error popup.

(In reply to comment #8) > Miles, please take another look at the description. I am requesting that it is > possible to _open_ the editor when offline without getting a modal error popup.
Steffen, I understand that. I agree that the current workflow is not very clean, but I'm pointing out that the user is presented with "a modal dialog when working offline" when doing common tasks. The issue is coming from a functional difference. With Reviews, we can't simply not retrieve the items as we need them every time we present to user and we are accomplishing that in a background job, so this isn't something we control directly. The only short-term solution is to downgrade the error status in the job to a warning. Would that be reasonable?

I agree that the current workflow is not very clean, > but I'm pointing out that the user is presented with "a modal dialog when > working offline" when doing common tasks.
That is true, when the user explicitly triggers repository operations such as refreshing or submitting tasks.
> The issue is coming from a functional > difference. With Reviews, we can't simply not retrieve the items as we need them > every time we present to user and we are accomplishing that in a background job, > so this isn't something we control directly.
That's fine but it should still be possible to view reviews without being prompted with a modal dialog when working offline. This worked previously and it's a key value proposition of the task editor.
> The only short-term solution is to > downgrade the error status in the job to a warning. Would that be reasonable?
No. The error has to be presented embedded in the editor and not in a modal dialog that requires another interaction.

> > The only short-term solution is to > > downgrade the error status in the job to a warning. Would that be reasonable? > > No. The error has to be presented embedded in the editor and not in a modal > dialog that requires another interaction.
On second thought, maybe yes. It depends on how that is presented and if there is sufficient indication in the UI of what is going on.
Miles, I would prefer not to put this regression into Kepler M6. Let me know if you'll have time to resolve it by tomorrow. The easiest solution could be to change the error handling to simply log instead of showing a dialog.

(In reply to comment #10) > > > possible to _open_ the editor when offline without getting a modal error > > popup. > > > > Steffen, I understand that. I agree that the current workflow is not very > clean, > > but I'm pointing out that the user is presented with "a modal dialog when > > working offline" when doing common tasks. > > That is true, when the user explicitly triggers repository operations such as > refreshing or submitting tasks.
What perhaps isn't clear is that the retrieval is happening asynchronously, triggerred by but independent of the actual editor opening. So what we're doing is essentially a background update. I understand that this should probably be user pull, but right now it cannot be. As I indicated above, we currently don't have a choice but to invoke the retrieval here, because except for the very basic task attributes, we don't have any significant data to show users and we won't until we have cross-workbench session persistence working.
> > The only short-term solution is to > > downgrade the error status in the job to a warning. Would that be reasonable? > > No. The error has to be presented embedded in the editor and not in a modal > dialog that requires another interaction.
You've missed my point. :) Because this is happening in a job, we can't prevent surfacing the error if one occurs and we return the status according to Job contract. So the only thing I can do in short-term is turn an error into a warning:
https://git.eclipse.org/r/#/c/11290/
But note again, that we won't even be using a single job per review in the future, so this isn't relevant for the long-term. As a reminder, I anticipated that precisely because we are impacting so many components at once, we aren't neccessarly gong to be able to preserve features across changes http://dev.eclipse.org/mhonarc/lists/mylyn-reviews-dev/msg00679.html. The only alternative would be to save all of the changes for review once everything is perfect, and we know that isn't a workable solution.
Hopefully this resolves your concern for M6. If you want it in, we can merge it asap. Really, M6 is not good timing, given that we're totally mid-stream here. I wouldn't be adverse to using a change-id from a few reviews back and releasing that as M6, but I don't know if that is even possible.
